ld fundamentally reject racism at its core. But the activists and reformers on the opposite side believed that the colonization movement was itself deeply racist and in fact one of the greatest obstacles for African Americans to gain citizenship in the United States.Power-Greene synthesizes debates about colonization and emigration, situating this complex and enduring issue into an ever broader conversation about nation building and identity formation in the Atlantic world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxColonizationxAfrica. 0aAfrican AmericansxColonizationzAfrica. 0aAntislavery movementsxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aAntislavery movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aBack to Africa movementxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479823178.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479876693423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479876693/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles